After Italy, Spain will also face the "lock-up" . It all seems to be happening so fast.

Until last weekend, Spain was singing and dancing as usual. 120,000 people marched in central Madrid to celebrate the International Women's Day, 80,000 fans watched the National Derby football match and 9,000 supporters of the political party rallied in a bullring.

But this past week, the epidemic has taken a turn for the worse. On March 14th SÁNCHEZ, the Prime Minister, announced a nationwide "siege" that would begin at 8am on March 16th. The law requires people to avoid going out except to buy food, medical supplies, go to the hospital, work or deal with other emergencies. This is a further escalation of the previous closures, which meant 47m Spaniards would have to stay at home.

Many Chinese from Valencia, Basque, Madrid told interface news that their basic life in Spain has not yet been affected. After the government declared a state of emergency on March 13th, supermarkets ran out of supplies and there were fewer people on the streets than usual, but few passers-by wore face masks.

###A tenfold increase in a week

As of the evening of March 14 local time, a total of 6,393 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed and 195 deaths had been reported in Spain. The Prime Minister's office also announced that his wife, Sánchez, had been diagnosed with the new coronavirus.

Spain has become the most affected country in Europe outside of Italy, with the fastest-growing number of cases.

From 500 to 5,000, it took South Korea 11 days, Italy 10 days, and Spain seven days. The surge of the past week has also helped Spain overtake more populous Germany and France to become Europe's second-most-affected country.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Trends in the Spanish epidemic. Source: WORLDOMETERS

The worst outbreak is in the capital, Madrid, which accounts for half of all confirmed cases and almost two-thirds of all deaths. Cluster infection in several nursing homes. The regional government of Madrid urgently assessed the health risks of the homes and closed two of them on 8 March.

As of March 11, all schools, nurseries and day-care centres for the elderly have been closed in the Madrid, Basque and La Rioja regions. On March 12th Catalonia cordoned off towns; on March 13th Sánchez, the Prime Minister, declared a state of emergency.

The earliest new crown cases in Spain were confirmed at the end of January and were imported cases from Germany. But both were quickly quarantined and discharged. On February 13, Spain suffered its first death from a new case of pneumonia, which was not confirmed at the time.

None of the first four deaths in Spain with NCP were confirmed alive. This suggests that experts are wrong about when the virus will arrive in Spain.

###The government is under fire

The Spanish government has come under fire for failing to prevent the disease.

"It is politicians, not professionals, who are fighting the epidemic, " Ngela Herndez Puente, Deputy secretary-general of the Trade Union Health Ministry in Madrid, told reporters. Spain is still responding to the crisis with a degree of complacency, and "obviously not good enough" .

Critics say the government failed to take action earlier to limit mass rallies.

According to the Spanish newspaper El Mundo, the Madrid regional government approved a total of 77 demonstrations on March 7 and 8, of which 55 took place on March 8.

The European Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (ECDC) on March 2 issued a warning to member states at risk of an outbreak to avoid unnecessary mass gatherings. The ECDC's recommendations clearly state that, as a "precautionary measure" , "No activity of more than, people should be held" during an outbreak. But the Spanish government did not take up the offer, even encouraging people to take to the streets in the name of "equality" .

The far-right Vox party held a rally of 9,000 people last weekend. But then three of the party's most senior figures -- including the party leader and the Party secretary -- were declared champions. In addition, two ministers in the SÁNCHEZ administration were confirmed.

That raises the question of whether policymakers know what to do about the virus?

Although Spain has one of the best health care in the European Union, the New York Times points out, it still faces the challenge of keeping health care in the hands of regional, not central, governments.

Prime Minister Sánchez, who heads a minority government on the left, came to power in an unsatisfying election earlier this year. "We have a very good health system in Spain, but the problem is that it is spread across 17 regions and is often controlled by politicians who are not usually wearing the same colour, " said Puente, a health union official

###Chinese under epidemic situation

Institutionally, Spain has 17 regions (district-province-city, three levels) , and different decisions require different governments to make, Lin Wei, a Chinese student from the Valencia region, told interface news. For example, the decision to suspend classes is made by the district, neither the city nor the school has the power.

Like Italians, Spaniards are naturally optimistic and confident about their health care systems, and both countries have high life expectancy, he told internetnews. Few people still wear masks on the streets.

"The first thing my friends thought of after declaring the state of emergency was to get one last drink before the restaurant and bar closed, " says linvey.

The Basque region is the region most affected by the outbreak. Xie Chunhui, a Chinese who lives in the Basque region of Saint-Sébastien, told interface news that the basic livelihood of the people has not been affected much.

The Basque government announced the suspension at 1 p.m. on March 12, and on that day many people went to the supermarket to buy milk powder, dishwashing detergent and so on, but there was no shortage of them, she told interface news. The first time I saw the supermarket out of stock was the afternoon of the 13th, lack of toilet paper, paper, kitchen paper, fresh fruits and vegetables, meat, bread, eggs, hand sanitizer, body wash. Saturday morning (14th) to see the basic replenishment has been.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In supermarkets in the Basque region, hygiene products have been snapped up. Source: Image courtesy of the respondents

"The ban will go into effect on Monday. There are still people in the streets today, but it's obviously quieter than usual, " Xie said.
